From: kem@prl.ufl.edu (Kelly Murray)
Crossposted-To: comp.windows.x.i386unix
Subject: Re: 2MB vs 1MB on 801 S3 ?
Date: 5 Nov 1993 15:58:54 GMT

In article <2bdhim$et5@harbinger.cc.monash.edu.au>, ins122a@aurora.cc.monash.edu.au (Mike Battersby) writes:
|> kem@prl.ufl.edu (Kelly Murray) writes:
|> >Additional memory should not affect the performance of the card.
|> >What is important is the speed of the memory, and the type of memory.
|> >Faster memory will speed things up, and VRAM boards will be faster 
|> >than DRAM boards.
|> 
|> Forgive me if I'm wrong, but don't S3 cards use non-display-used video
|> ram for caching purposes (for bitblt operations and such). Thus,
|> wouldnt an extra meg of ram increase the cache size and thus
|> performance?
|> 

A little cache goes a very long way -- a lot of cache only goes farther if
the server puts it to good use.  Jon provides the current answer:

>From: jon@robots.ox.ac.uk (Jon Tombs)
>All off screen memory will be used as cache, it would mean you cache pixmaps
>of upto 256x256, and several hundred more fonts than you would ever want.
>If you spen a lot of time moving big pixmaps around then this might be
>important to you. But the caching of the xfree86-2.0 servers is still far to
>primative to make much advantage of the extra ram (should improve with time
>though).

The large surplus cache is best used for backing store.  This makes a huge
difference in interactive performance for networked machines,
since you don't need to generate expose events and do the screen updates
using network X protocol traffic.  Looking at the sources, it doesn't
look like this is implemented right now in XFree2.0.  The benefit isn't
as big for local-connection clients -- typical useage 
for standalone PC's running local clients.

-- 
-- Kelly Murray  (kem@prl.ufl.edu) 
University of Florida Parallel Research Lab  :: 96-node KSR1, 64-node nCUBE
