From: morley@suncad.camosun.bc.ca (Mark Morley)
Subject: Another success story.
Date: Fri, 5 Nov 1993 05:46:22 GMT

Well, it's taken a couple of months, but I've finally done it.  Whew!
Some of you may remember that I was working on setting up a BBS based on
Linux boxes, etc.  IT'S ALIVE!  Muahahahah!

The BBS (Island Net) is attached to the Internet 24 hours a day via a
leased line.  I am using PCRoute running on a 386dx/20 as my IP router. 
It connects via SLIP to a NetBlazer somewhere over Courier modems.

I currently have two Linux hosts on the network (all machines are
connected to a thinnet backbone).  The smaller "utility" host is just a
386dx/40.  It has 8 megs of ram, 120 meg IDE drive, 205 meg IDE drive, and
an SMC card.  It is running SLS 1.03 straight.

The second host is the main BBS machine.  It is a 486dx/50 with 16 megs of
ram, Adaptec 1542cf SCSI card, Micropolis 1.2 gig fast SCSI 2 drive, and
(as of tonight) an NEC 84 SCSI CD ROM.  This one has a serial card with 2
16550A's on it and two US Robotics Sporster 14.4 modems attached.  I want
to add a 4 port card soon (likely one of those STB thingies).  This one is
also running SLS 1.03 straight.

The BBS itself is written in M-Script, which is a programming language I
developed just for writing BBS's.  M-Script still needs a _lot_ of work,
but it's doing pretty good so far.

(ASIDE: What's with all these posts about SCSI under Linux being slow? 
Since I replaced my IDE drive with this SCSI one, my disk access is at
least twice as fast.  A search of the entire disk for any particular file
takes a whole 2 seconds - no lie)

Tonight I finished setting up DNS on the main machine - it seems to be
working well.  I've been live on the 'net now for over a week.  All
telnet's/ftp's/etc have worked flawlessly.

All I can say is: WOW! Linus and crew, you've done a tremendous job.  If
you're ever up my way I'll buy you a drink.

I'll be happy to try and answer any questions you might have about my setup.

Cheers!

Mark

